<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <DIV ID='content_title' STYLE='font-size: 120%; '>ICS Day 2015 keeps students involved and connected</DIV><P>June 8, 2015<p>


<P>
<STRONG>This year&rsquo;s annual student-run tech carnival was filled with swag and selfies.</STRONG>


<P>
<object width="450" height="338"> <param name="flashvars" value="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157653226652181%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157653226652181%2F&set_id=72157653226652181&jump_to="></param> <param name="movie" value="https://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=1811922554"></param> <param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" src="https://www.flickr.com/apps/slideshow/show.swf?v=1811922554" allowFullScreen="true" flashvars="offsite=true&lang=en-us&page_show_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157653226652181%2Fshow%2F&page_show_back_url=%2Fphotos%2Fbrenschool%2Fsets%2F72157653226652181%2F&set_id=72157653226652181&jump_to=" width="450" height="338"></embed></object>




<P>
As students drift into the Computer Game Science (COGS) Lab, a barrage of colors, sounds and pixels encircles them. The source: a large selection of student-produced video games. 

<P>
Jason Chu, vice president of the Video Game Development Club (VGDC), guides visiting students through their options: There&rsquo;s <I>Airpacas</I>, a Tron-inspired game with cutesy graphics where players compete against each other with blue and pink airborne alpacas. Next to it, the graphically simple <I>Monopoley</I>, where players are tasked with an equally simple objective: Don&rsquo;t die. 


<P>
But at the center of the room is the biggest attraction &mdash; a demo of the Oculus Rift virtual reality headset, where users can preview an educational project that simulates the former Elmina Castle &ldquo;slave fort&rdquo; in Ghana. The project, designed by Allen Roman and Hongde Jin, comes out of the ICS computer game science capstone class.

 
<P>
Just outside the COGS Lab door, ICS Student Council&rsquo;s (ICSSC) annual tech student carnival diffuses throughout the ICS-Engineering Hall Plaza. It&rsquo;s ICS Day 2015!

 
<P>
Started in 2012, ICS Day is ICSSC&rsquo;s largest annual event&mdash;and every year, they manage to make it bigger and better. &ldquo;We implemented a lot of new things for this year's ICS Day, with the main ones being the raffle ticket system and the swag booth,&rdquo; ICSSC Vice President Stephanie Chang said, referring to the Google Swag booth, where attendees traded raffle tickets for goodies like Google blankets and duffle bags.

 
<P>
In addition to the new celebratory additions, there were familiar holdovers, including the annual coding competitions, as well as performances from dance group MCIA, a capella group Uniting Voices and band AnonJ. Though it was a dragon-shaped bounce house that served as the festival&rsquo;s beacon, with its giant, bobbing head that could be spotted from Aldrich Park.

 
<P>
ICS student organizations and corporate recruiters tabled the event, hosting activities and promoting their missions to interested ears. The UCI branch of the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) held coding competitions that culminated in sparring with ICS Lecturer Alex Thornton. Across the plaza, IT Consulting Firm Pariveda Solutions hosted a toy-boat building and racing competition, whereby students engineered boats powered by blowing through a straw. Attendees also crowded into the selfie booth, wrapping themselves in feather boas and donning funny hats as they flashed their zot hands.

 
<P>
&ldquo;Students were a lot more involved throughout the event this year, attending our coding competitions and taking pictures in the selfie booth to get more tickets to exchange for tons of swag and to enter our raffles for $50 Amazon gift cards and an Apple TV,&rdquo; Chang said.

 
<P>
ICS Day takes ICSSC months to plan. As ICSSC President Delian Petrov noted <A HREF="http://www.ics.uci.edu/community/news/features/view_feature?id=4">last year</A>, &ldquo;We plan the budget, the events, the food, the shirts and then we plan for when what we planned changes 180 degrees.&rdquo;

 
<P>
All the planning panned out, Chang said. &ldquo;I think ICS Day was especially well received this year, and I can't wait for next year!&rdquo;





<!-- -->
<!-- -->
</p>
<div style="float: right; margin: 1em 0;"> 
   &#8212; Story by Courtney Hamilton <br />
   &#8212; Video by Robert Farmer <br />
   &#8212; Photos by Matt Miller <br />
